","1120–1149":"1120–1149","1139–1200":"1139–1200","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1200":"1200","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucester County, England":"Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England"},"nl":{"1122–1160":"1122–1160","1120–1149":"1120–1149","1139–1200":"1139–1200","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1200":"1200","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucester County, England":"Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1122–1160":"1122–1160","1120–1149":"1120–1149","1139–1200":"1139–1200","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1200":"1200","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucester County, England":"Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Palmer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>palmer(e)</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim to the Holy Land’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>palmer</i>, Old French <i>pa(l)mer</i>, <i>paum(i)er</i>), so called from the palm branch carried by such pilgrims. The term was also used to denote an itinerant monk who traveled from shrine to shrine under a vow of poverty. This surname is also common in Ireland, where it has been recorded from the 13th century onward.","Irish: when not of English origin (see 1 above), a surname adopted for Gaelic <b>Ó Maolfhoghmhair</b> (see   Milford  ), the name of an ecclesiastical family.","Swedish (mainly <b>Palmér</b>): ornamental name formed with <i>palm</i> ‘palm tree’ + the suffix <i>-ér</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>-erius</i>) or <i>-er</i> (from German)."],"variants":[{"name":"Milford","meanings":["English (mainly Devon): habitational name from any of the many places called Milford, deriving from Old English <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","Irish (Antrim and Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maolfhoghmhair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maolgfhoghmhair</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘chief of harvest’. The Irish name was first Anglicized as <b>Mullover</b>, which was later assimilated to <i>Milford</i>. See also   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Palmiere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Dante, Enrico, Nicola, Salvatore, Vittorio.","Italian: from <i>palmiere</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim’. See   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Parmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Palmer  .","Indian (northern states): variant of   Parmar  ."]},{"name":"Palmore","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Palmer   or an Americanized form of South German   Balmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry De Palmer II was born in 1122, in Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Sir Henry de Palmer I, was 22 and his mother, Lady Anna Walton, was 23. He married Lady Ann de Walton in 1140, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1160, in England, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1122–1160":"1122–1160","1120–1149":"1120–1149","1139–1200":"1139–1200","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1200":"1200","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucester County, England":"Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1122–1160":"1122–1160","1120–1149":"1120–1149","1139–1200":"1139–1200","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1200":"1200","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucester County, England":"Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",